<!-- FAQ -->
<section id="faq" class="faq-section">
    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What size is an Olympic Queen mattress?</h3>
        <p>An Olympic Queen mattress measures 66 inches wide by 80 inches long. It's 6 inches wider than a standard Queen (60x80) and 10 inches narrower than a King (76x80).</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Is Olympic Queen the same as RV Queen?</h3>
        <p>Not exactly. "RV Queen" can refer to several sizes depending on the manufacturer. The most common RV size is the Short Queen (60x75), which is different from an Olympic Queen (66x80). Always measure your actual bed to confirm the size you need.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Why is my Olympic Queen mattress so hard to replace?</h3>
        <p>Olympic Queen was introduced in 1999 but never became a standard industry size. Most mattress retailers only stock Twin, Full, Queen, King, and California King. Olympic Queen is considered a "custom" or "specialty" size, which means fewer manufacturers make it and retail stores don't stock it.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How long does an Olympic Queen mattress last?</h3>
        <p>With quality materials, 7-10 years is typical. However, we regularly see Olympic Queens that are 15-20 years old ‚Äî not because they last longer, but because owners don't know where to buy replacements. Don't do this. A worn-out mattress affects your sleep quality and health.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Can I use King size sheets on an Olympic Queen?</h3>
        <p>King sheets are 76x80, while Olympic Queen is 66x80. They're the same length but 10 inches wider. King sheets will fit but will be loose on the sides. For a proper fit, look for Olympic Queen specific sheets or have custom sheets made.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Where can I try an Olympic Queen mattress before buying?</h3>
        <p>Most Olympic Queen mattresses are only available online. However, many brands (like Brooklyn Bedding and Mattress Insider) have showrooms where you can try their mattresses in standard sizes ‚Äî the feel will be the same regardless of size.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What's the best Olympic Queen mattress for couples?</h3>
        <p>For most couples, we recommend the Brooklyn Signature Hybrid. It offers good motion isolation (so you don't feel your partner moving), comes in multiple firmness levels, and provides the support and durability couples need. The edge support is excellent, so you can both use the full width of the mattress.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Is it worth buying an expensive Olympic Queen mattress?</h3>
        <p>It depends on how often you use it. If it's your primary bed and you sleep on it every night, invest in quality ‚Äî a $1,000-1,500 mattress that lasts 10 years costs less than $0.50 per night. If it's for a guest room used occasionally, a more affordable option like the Dreamfoam Essential is fine.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How does memory foam feel different in an RV?</h3>
        <p>Memory foam is temperature-sensitive. In cold weather, it feels firmer as the foam hardens. In warm weather, it feels softer. This is normal for all memory foam ‚Äî just something to be aware of if you're camping in varying climates. If this concerns you, consider a hybrid or innerspring option instead.</p>
    </div>
